# Fix font rendering issues
import matplotlib
import platform

def setup_fonts():
    """Setup fonts to avoid rendering issues"""
    try:
        # Get system info
        system = platform.system()
        print(f"System: {system}")
        
        # Available font families
        available_fonts = matplotlib.font_manager.get_font_names()
        
        # Priority list of fonts (from most preferred to fallback)
        font_priorities = [
            'DejaVu Sans',      # Usually available on most systems
            'Arial',            # Common on Windows
            'Helvetica',        # Common on macOS
            'Liberation Sans',  # Common on Linux
            'sans-serif'        # Generic fallback
        ]
        
        # Find first available font
        selected_font = 'sans-serif'  # Default fallback
        for font in font_priorities:
            if font in available_fonts or font == 'sans-serif':
                selected_font = font
                break
        
        print(f"Selected font: {selected_font}")
        
        # Configure matplotlib to use the selected font
        plt.rcParams['font.family'] = selected_font
        plt.rcParams['font.sans-serif'] = [selected_font]
        
        # Disable font warnings and use fallback for missing glyphs
        plt.rcParams['axes.unicode_minus'] = False
        
        # Set other font-related parameters
        plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 10
        plt.rcParams['axes.titlesize'] = 12
        plt.rcParams['axes.labelsize'] = 10
        plt.rcParams['xtick.labelsize'] = 9
        plt.rcParams['ytick.labelsize'] = 9
        plt.rcParams['legend.fontsize'] = 9
        
        return True
        
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Font setup warning: {e}")
        print("Using matplotlib defaults")
        return False

# Setup fonts
font_setup_success = setup_fonts()

# Set up plotting style
plt.style.use('default')
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (14, 10)

# Additional matplotlib settings to handle special characters

# Function to clean text for better rendering
def clean_text_for_display(text):
    """Clean text to avoid font rendering issues"""
    # Replace common problematic Unicode characters with ASCII equivalents
    replacements = {
        '': '[Chart]',
        '': '[Up]',
        '': '[Down]',
        '': '[Predict]',
        '': '[Money]',
        '': '[Target]',
        '': '[Warning]',
        '': '[Check]',
        '': '[Rocket]',
        '': '[Cycle]',
        '': '[Idea]',
        '': '[Building]',
        '': '[Computer]',
        '': '[Science]',
        '': '[People]',
        '': '[Tool]',
        '': '[Alert]',
        '': '[Yellow]',
        '': '[Green]',
        '': '[Red]',
        '': '-',  # En dash to hyphen
        '': '-',  # Em dash to hyphen
        ''': "'",  # Smart quote to straight quote
        ''': "'",  # Smart quote to straight quote
        '"': '"',  # Smart quote to straight quote
        '"': '"',  # Smart quote to straight quote
    }
    
    cleaned_text = str(text)
    for unicode_char, ascii_replacement in replacements.items():
        cleaned_text = cleaned_text.replace(unicode_char, ascii_replacement)
    
    return cleaned_text

# 5-Year Analysis Benefits and Data Quality Assessment
print(" 5-YEAR NVDA ANALYSIS - ENHANCED INSIGHTS")
print("="*60)

if len(stock_data) > 0:
    years_of_data = (stock_data.index[-1] - stock_data.index[0]).days / 365.25
    
    print(f" DATASET OVERVIEW:")
    print(f" Actual data span: {years_of_data:.1f} years")
    print(f" Trading days: {len(stock_data):,}")
    print(f" Average trading days per year: {len(stock_data)/years_of_data:.0f}")
    
    # Calculate key metrics over the 5-year period
    total_return = ((stock_data['Close'].iloc[-1] / stock_data['Close'].iloc[0]) - 1) * 100
    annualized_return = ((stock_data['Close'].iloc[-1] / stock_data['Close'].iloc[0]) ** (1/years_of_data) - 1) * 100
    
    # Volatility metrics
    daily_returns = stock_data['Close'].pct_change().dropna()
    daily_volatility = daily_returns.std()
    annualized_volatility = daily_volatility * np.sqrt(252) * 100
    
    # Drawdown analysis
    cumulative_returns = (1 + daily_returns).cumprod()
    running_max = cumulative_returns.expanding().max()
    drawdown = (cumulative_returns - running_max) / running_max
    max_drawdown = drawdown.min() * 100
    
    print(f"\n 5-YEAR PERFORMANCE METRICS:")
    print(f" Total Return: {total_return:+.1f}%")
    print(f" Annualized Return: {annualized_return:+.1f}%")
    print(f" Annualized Volatility: {annualized_volatility:.1f}%")
    print(f" Maximum Drawdown: {max_drawdown:.1f}%")
    print(f" Sharpe Ratio (approx): {annualized_return/annualized_volatility:.2f}")
    
    # Price range analysis
    price_range = stock_data['High'].max() - stock_data['Low'].min()
    current_price = stock_data['Close'].iloc[-1]
    
    print(f"\n PRICE ANALYSIS:")
    print(f" All-time high (5Y): ${stock_data['High'].max():.2f}")
    print(f" All-time low (5Y): ${stock_data['Low'].min():.2f}")
    print(f" Price range: ${price_range:.2f}")
    print(f" Current price: ${current_price:.2f}")
    print(f" Distance from 5Y high: {((current_price/stock_data['High'].max())-1)*100:.1f}%")
    print(f" Distance from 5Y low: {((current_price/stock_data['Low'].min())-1)*100:.1f}%")
    
    # Market cycles analysis
    print(f"\n MARKET CYCLES CAPTURED:")
    yearly_returns = []
    for year in range(int(stock_data.index[0].year), int(stock_data.index[-1].year) + 1):
        year_data = stock_data[stock_data.index.year == year]
        if len(year_data) > 10:  # Ensure sufficient data
            year_return = ((year_data['Close'].iloc[-1] / year_data['Close'].iloc[0]) - 1) * 100
            yearly_returns.append((year, year_return))
            print(f" {year}: {year_return:+.1f}%")
    
    print(f"\n ADVANTAGES OF 5-YEAR ANALYSIS:")
    print(" Captures multiple market cycles and economic conditions")
    print(" Includes various market regimes (bull, bear, sideways)")
    print(" Provides robust statistical foundation for ML models")
    print(" Enables long-term trend and seasonality analysis")
    print(" Reduces impact of short-term market noise")
    print(f" Large sample size ({len(stock_data):,} observations) improves model reliability")
    
    if years_of_data >= 4.5:
        print(" Excellent: Full 5-year dataset available for comprehensive analysis")
    elif years_of_data >= 3.5:
        print(" Good: Near 5-year dataset provides solid analytical foundation")
    else:
        print(" Limited: Less than 4 years of data may limit long-term analysis")

else:
    print(" No data available for analysis")

print("\n" + "="*60)

# Enhanced Feature Engineering with Market and Options Data
def create_features(data, sp500_data=None, vix_data=None, options_data=None):
    """Create comprehensive features for ML model including market context and options"""
    df = data.copy()
    
    print("Creating enhanced features with market context...")
    print(f"Input data shape: {df.shape}")
    
    # Performance optimization for larger datasets
    if len(df) > 1000:
        print("Large dataset detected - optimizing feature calculations...")
    
    # Basic price features
    df['Price_Change'] = df['Close'].pct_change()
    df['High_Low_Pct'] = (df['High'] - df['Low']) / df['Close']
    df['Price_Range'] = df['High'] - df['Low']
    
    # Volume features
    df['Volume_Change'] = df['Volume'].pct_change()
    df['Volume_Price_Ratio'] = df['Volume'] / df['Close']
    
    # Moving averages - enhanced for 5-year analysis
    # Short-term (days), medium-term (weeks), long-term (months/quarters)
    ma_windows = [5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200] if len(df) > 500 else [5, 10, 20, 50]
    
    for window in ma_windows:
        df[f'MA_{window}'] = df['Close'].rolling(window=window).mean()
        df[f'MA_{window}_ratio'] = df['Close'] / df[f'MA_{window}']
        df[f'MA_{window}_slope'] = df[f'MA_{window}'].diff()
        
    # Long-term trend analysis (only for 5-year data)
    if len(df) > 1000:
        print("Adding long-term trend features for 5-year analysis...")
        df['MA_252'] = df['Close'].rolling(window=252).mean()  # 1-year MA
        df['MA_252_ratio'] = df['Close'] / df['MA_252']
        
        # Quarterly performance features
        df['Quarter'] = df.index.quarter
        df['Year'] = df.index.year
    
    # Technical indicators
    # RSI
    delta = df['Close'].diff()
    gain = (delta.where(delta > 0, 0)).rolling(window=14).mean()
    loss = (-delta.where(delta < 0, 0)).rolling(window=14).mean()
    rs = gain / loss
    df['RSI'] = 100 - (100 / (1 + rs))
    
    # Bollinger Bands
    df['BB_Middle'] = df['Close'].rolling(window=20).mean()
    bb_std = df['Close'].rolling(window=20).std()
    df['BB_Upper'] = df['BB_Middle'] + (bb_std * 2)
    df['BB_Lower'] = df['BB_Middle'] - (bb_std * 2)
    df['BB_Width'] = (df['BB_Upper'] - df['BB_Lower']) / df['BB_Middle']
    df['BB_Position'] = (df['Close'] - df['BB_Lower']) / (df['BB_Upper'] - df['BB_Lower'])
    
    # MACD
    exp1 = df['Close'].ewm(span=12).mean()
    exp2 = df['Close'].ewm(span=26).mean()
    df['MACD'] = exp1 - exp2
    df['MACD_Signal'] = df['MACD'].ewm(span=9).mean()
    df['MACD_Histogram'] = df['MACD'] - df['MACD_Signal']
    
    # Volatility (standard deviation of returns)
    df['Volatility_5'] = df['Price_Change'].rolling(window=5).std()
    df['Volatility_20'] = df['Price_Change'].rolling(window=20).std()
    
    # Lagged features - enhanced for 5-year data
    # Include both short-term and medium-term lags
    short_lags = range(1, 6)  # 1-5 days
    medium_lags = [7, 14, 21] if len(df) > 500 else []  # Weekly patterns
    
    for lag in short_lags:
        df[f'Close_lag_{lag}'] = df['Close'].shift(lag)
        df[f'Change_lag_{lag}'] = df['Price_Change'].shift(lag)
        df[f'Volume_lag_{lag}'] = df['Volume'].shift(lag)
    
    # Medium-term lags for long-term patterns (5-year data)
    for lag in medium_lags:
        df[f'Close_lag_{lag}'] = df['Close'].shift(lag)
        df[f'Change_lag_{lag}'] = df['Price_Change'].shift(lag)
    
    # Target variable (next day's closing price)
    df['Target'] = df['Close'].shift(-1)
    df['Target_Change'] = df['Target'] / df['Close'] - 1
    
    # Day of week effect
    df['DayOfWeek'] = df.index.dayofweek
    df['IsMonday'] = (df['DayOfWeek'] == 0).astype(int)
    df['IsFriday'] = (df['DayOfWeek'] == 4).astype(int)
    
    # S&P 500 market features
    if sp500_data is not None:
        print("Adding S&P 500 market features...")
        # Align S&P 500 data with stock data
        common_idx = df.index.intersection(sp500_data.index)
        
        for idx in common_idx:
            if idx in df.index and idx in sp500_data.index:
                # S&P 500 price and returns
                df.loc[idx, 'SP500_Close'] = sp500_data.loc[idx, 'Close']
                df.loc[idx, 'SP500_Volume'] = sp500_data.loc[idx, 'Volume']
        
        # Calculate S&P 500 features
        if 'SP500_Close' in df.columns:
            df['SP500_Return'] = df['SP500_Close'].pct_change()
            df['SP500_MA_20'] = df['SP500_Close'].rolling(window=20).mean()
            df['SP500_Volatility'] = df['SP500_Return'].rolling(window=20).std()
            
            # Relative performance vs S&P 500
            df['Beta_vs_SP500'] = df['Price_Change'].rolling(window=20).corr(df['SP500_Return'])
            df['Relative_Strength'] = df['Close'] / df['SP500_Close'] * 1000  # Normalized
            df['Outperformance'] = df['Price_Change'] - df['SP500_Return']
    
    # VIX features (market fear gauge)
    if vix_data is not None:
        print("Adding VIX volatility features...")
        common_idx = df.index.intersection(vix_data.index)
        
        for idx in common_idx:
            if idx in df.index and idx in vix_data.index:
                df.loc[idx, 'VIX'] = vix_data.loc[idx, 'Close']
        
        if 'VIX' in df.columns:
            df['VIX_Change'] = df['VIX'].pct_change()
            df['VIX_MA_10'] = df['VIX'].rolling(window=10).mean()
            df['VIX_High'] = (df['VIX'] > 30).astype(int)  # Fear indicator
            df['VIX_Low'] = (df['VIX'] < 20).astype(int)   # Complacency indicator
    
    # Options-derived features (current snapshot applied to all dates)
    if options_data is not None:
        print("Adding options-derived features...")
        # These are current options metrics applied as constant features
        # In practice, you'd want historical options data for better features
        df['Implied_Volatility'] = options_data.get('call_iv', 0)
        df['IV_Skew'] = options_data.get('iv_skew', 0)
        df['Put_Call_Ratio'] = options_data.get('pc_ratio', 0)
        df['Options_Volume_Ratio'] = (options_data.get('call_volume', 0) + 
                                     options_data.get('put_volume', 0)) / df['Volume'].rolling(20).mean()
        
        # Options sentiment indicators
        df['Bullish_Options'] = (options_data.get('pc_ratio', 1) < 0.8).astype(int)
        df['Bearish_Options'] = (options_data.get('pc_ratio', 1) > 1.2).astype(int)
        df['High_IV'] = (options_data.get('call_iv', 0) > 0.5).astype(int)
    
    # Market regime features
    # Trend strength
    df['Trend_Strength'] = abs(df['Close'].rolling(20).apply(lambda x: np.polyfit(range(len(x)), x, 1)[0]))
    
    # Volatility regime
    df['Vol_Regime'] = (df['Volatility_20'] > df['Volatility_20'].rolling(60).mean()).astype(int)
    
    # Market cap effect (for large caps like NVDA, less sensitive to small-cap factors)
    df['Large_Cap_Factor'] = 1  # NVDA is always large cap
    
    print(f"Final feature set shape: {df.shape}")
    feature_count = len([col for col in df.columns if col not in 
                        ['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close', 'Volume', 'Dividends', 'Stock Splits', 
                         'Target', 'Target_Change']])
    print(f"Total engineered features: {feature_count}")
    
    return df

# Create enhanced features with market and options data

)

# Prepare data for machine learning
def prepare_ml_data(df):
    """Prepare clean data for ML models"""
    
    # Select feature columns (exclude original OHLCV and target columns)
    feature_cols = [col for col in df.columns if col not in 
                   ['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close', 'Volume', 'Dividends', 'Stock Splits', 
                    'Target', 'Target_Change']]
    
    # Create clean dataset
    ml_data = df[feature_cols + ['Target', 'Target_Change']].copy()
    
    # Remove rows with missing values
    ml_data_clean = ml_data.dropna()
    
    print(f"Original data shape: {df.shape}")
    print(f"ML data shape after removing NaN: {ml_data_clean.shape}")
    print(f"Features selected: {len(feature_cols)}")
    
    return ml_data_clean, feature_cols

# Train Multiple ML Models for Price Prediction
print("Training multiple machine learning models...")

# Define models
models = {
    'Random Forest': RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1),
    'Gradient Boosting': GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    'Linear Regression': Pipeline([
        ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
        ('regressor', LinearRegression())
    ]),
    'XGBoost': XGBRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    'K-Nearest Neighbors': KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=5),
    'Support Vector Regression': SVR(kernel='rbf', C=1.0, epsilon=0.1),
    'Decision Tree': DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=10, random_state=42),
    'Neural Network': MLPRegressor(hidden_layer_sizes=(100, 50), max_iter=1000, random_state=42),
    'Ridge Regression': Ridge(alpha=1.0),
    'Lasso Regression': Lasso(alpha=0.1),
    'ElasticNet Regression': ElasticNet(alpha=0.1, l1_ratio=0.5),
    'AdaBoost': AdaBoostRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    'Bagging': BaggingRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    'Extra Trees': ExtraTreesRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    'Stochastic Gradient Descent': SGDRegressor(max_iter=1000, random_state=42),
    'LGBM': LGBMRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    'CatBoost': CatBoostRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
    #'LightGBM': LightGBMRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
}

# Train models and evaluate performance
model_results = {}
trained_models = {}

for name, model in models.items():
    print(f"\nTraining {name}...")
    
    # Train the model
    model.fit(X_train, y_price_train)
    trained_models[name] = model
    
    # Make predictions
    y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Calculate metrics
    train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_price_train, y_pred_train)
    test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_price_test, y_pred_test)
    train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_price_train, y_pred_train)
    test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_price_test, y_pred_test)
    train_r2 = r2_score(y_price_train, y_pred_train)
    test_r2 = r2_score(y_price_test, y_pred_test)
    
    # Cross-validation score
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_price_train, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
    cv_rmse = np.sqrt(-cv_scores.mean())
    
    model_results[name] = {
        'train_mse': train_mse,
        'test_mse': test_mse,
        'train_mae': train_mae,
        'test_mae': test_mae,
        'train_r2': train_r2,
        'test_r2': test_r2,
        'cv_rmse': cv_rmse,
        'predictions': y_pred_test
    }
    
    print(f"  Train R: {train_r2:.4f}, Test R: {test_r2:.4f}")
    print(f"  Train RMSE: ${np.sqrt(train_mse):.2f}, Test RMSE: ${np.sqrt(test_mse):.2f}")
    print(f"  CV RMSE: ${cv_rmse:.2f}")

# Select best model based on test R
best_model_name = max(model_results.keys(), key=lambda x: model_results[x]['test_r2'])
best_model = trained_models[best_model_name]

print(f"\n{'='*50}")
print(f"BEST MODEL: {best_model_name}")
print(f"Test R Score: {model_results[best_model_name]['test_r2']:.4f}")
print(f"Test RMSE: ${np.sqrt(model_results[best_model_name]['test_mse']):.2f}")
print(f"{'='*50}")

# Display detailed results table
results_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': list(model_results.keys()),

# Multi-Horizon Price Predictions with Error Estimates
print(" GENERATING MULTI-HORIZON PRICE PREDICTIONS...")
print("="*60)

# Define prediction horizons (in trading days) - Extended for 1-year forward analysis
horizons = {
    '1 Week': 5,
    '2 Weeks': 10,
    '1 Month': 22,  # ~22 trading days in a month
    '2 Months': 44,
    '3 Months': 66,  # ~66 trading days in 3 months
    '6 Months': 132,  # ~132 trading days in 6 months
    '9 Months': 198,
    '1 Year': 252  # ~252 trading days in a year
}

def predict_multi_horizon_prices_improved(model, last_features, horizons_dict, feature_columns, historical_data):
    """Predict prices for multiple time horizons with improved methodology"""
    current_price = historical_data['Close'].iloc[-1]
    predictions_dict = {}
    
    # Calculate historical statistics for more robust predictions
    returns = historical_data['Close'].pct_change().dropna()
    daily_volatility = returns.std()
    mean_return = returns.mean()
    
    # Get recent price trend for baseline
    recent_prices = historical_data['Close'].tail(20)
    recent_trend = (recent_prices.iloc[-1] / recent_prices.iloc[0]) ** (1/20) - 1  # Daily trend
    
    print(f"Current price: ${current_price:.2f}")
    print(f"Daily volatility: {daily_volatility*100:.2f}%")
    print(f"Recent 20-day trend: {recent_trend*100:.3f}% per day")
    
    for horizon_name, days in horizons_dict.items():
        print(f"\nProcessing {horizon_name} ({days} days)...")
        
        # Method 1: Simple trend extrapolation with volatility
        trend_prediction = current_price * ((1 + recent_trend) ** days)
        
        # Method 2: Random walk with drift (more conservative)
        drift_prediction = current_price * ((1 + mean_return) ** days)
        
        # Method 3: ML model prediction (single step, more reliable)
        try:
            # Use the model for a single prediction, then apply statistical methods
            next_day_pred = model.predict(last_features.reshape(1, -1))[0]
            next_day_return = (next_day_pred / current_price) - 1
            
            # Extrapolate this return over the horizon (with decay)
            # Apply decay factor to prevent unrealistic long-term predictions
            decay_factor = max(0.1, 1 / np.sqrt(days))  # Decay for longer horizons
            adjusted_return = next_day_return * decay_factor
            ml_prediction = current_price * ((1 + adjusted_return) ** days)
            
        except Exception as e:
            print(f"ML prediction failed: {e}")
            ml_prediction = current_price  # Fallback to current price
        
        # Combine predictions with weighted average
        # Weight recent trend more for short term, mean reversion for long term
        if days <= 22:  # Short term (1 month or less)
            weights = [0.4, 0.2, 0.4]  # Favor trend and ML
        elif days <= 132:  # Medium term (6 months or less)
            weights = [0.3, 0.4, 0.3]  # Balanced
        else:  # Long term
            weights = [0.2, 0.6, 0.2]  # Favor mean reversion
        
        final_prediction = (weights[0] * trend_prediction + 
                          weights[1] * drift_prediction + 
                          weights[2] * ml_prediction)
        
        # Ensure prediction is reasonable (not negative, not too extreme)
        min_reasonable = current_price * 0.1  # Don't go below 10% of current
        max_reasonable = current_price * 10.0  # Don't go above 10x current
        final_prediction = np.clip(final_prediction, min_reasonable, max_reasonable)
        
        # Calculate statistics
        price_change = final_prediction - current_price
        price_change_pct = (price_change / current_price) * 100
        
        # Improved error estimation
        # Base error on historical volatility, model uncertainty, and time horizon
        base_error = daily_volatility * np.sqrt(days) * current_price
        
        # Add model uncertainty (higher for worse models)
        model_r2 = model_results[best_model_name]['test_r2'] if 'model_results' in globals() else 0
        model_uncertainty = max(0.1, 1 - max(0, model_r2))  # Higher uncertainty for negative R
        
        # Adjust error based on time horizon (longer = more uncertain)
        time_factor = 1 + (days / 252) * 0.5  # 50% more uncertainty per year
        
        prediction_error = base_error * model_uncertainty * time_factor
        confidence_95 = 1.96 * prediction_error
        
        predictions_dict[horizon_name] = {
            'days': days,
            'predicted_price': final_prediction,
            'current_price': current_price,
            'price_change': price_change,
            'price_change_pct': price_change_pct,
            'prediction_error': prediction_error,
            'confidence_95': confidence_95,
            'lower_bound': max(0, final_prediction - confidence_95),  # Ensure non-negative
            'upper_bound': final_prediction + confidence_95,
            'method_breakdown': {
                'trend_pred': trend_prediction,
                'drift_pred': drift_prediction,
                'ml_pred': ml_prediction,
                'weights': weights
            }
        }
        
        print(f"  Trend method: ${trend_prediction:.2f}")
        print(f"  Drift method: ${drift_prediction:.2f}")
        print(f"  ML method: ${ml_prediction:.2f}")
        print(f"  Final prediction: ${final_prediction:.2f} ({price_change_pct:+.1f}%)")
    
    return predictions_dict

# Generate multi-horizon predictions using improved methodology

# Get last year data
stock_1year = stock_data[stock_data.index >= start_date_1y].copy()

# Get corresponding S&P 500 and VIX data for the same period
if 'sp500_aligned' in locals() and sp500_aligned is not None:
    sp500_1year = sp500_aligned[sp500_aligned.index >= start_date_1y].copy()
else:
    sp500_1year = None

if 'vix_aligned' in locals() and vix_aligned is not None:
    vix_1year = vix_aligned[vix_aligned.index >= start_date_1y].copy()
else:
    vix_1year = None

print(f" 1-Year Period: {start_date_1y.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')} to {end_date_1y.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')}")
print(f" Stock Data: {len(stock_1year)} trading days")
print(f" S&P 500 Data: {len(sp500_1year) if sp500_1year is not None else 0} days")
print(f" VIX Data: {len(vix_1year) if vix_1year is not None else 0} days")

# Calculate 1-year performance metrics
if len(stock_1year) > 0:
    price_start_1y = stock_1year['Close'].iloc[0]
    price_end_1y = stock_1year['Close'].iloc[-1]
    return_1y = ((price_end_1y / price_start_1y) - 1) * 100
    
    # Volatility and risk metrics
    daily_returns_1y = stock_1year['Close'].pct_change().dropna()
    volatility_1y = daily_returns_1y.std() * np.sqrt(252) * 100
    
    # Drawdown analysis
    cumulative_1y = (1 + daily_returns_1y).cumprod()
    running_max_1y = cumulative_1y.expanding().max()
    drawdown_1y = (cumulative_1y - running_max_1y) / running_max_1y
    max_drawdown_1y = drawdown_1y.min() * 100
    
    print(f"\n 1-YEAR PERFORMANCE:")
    print(f" Starting Price: ${price_start_1y:.2f}")
    print(f" Current Price: ${price_end_1y:.2f}")
    print(f" 1-Year Return: {return_1y:+.1f}%")
    print(f" 1-Year Volatility: {volatility_1y:.1f}%")
    print(f" Max Drawdown: {max_drawdown_1y:.1f}%")
    
    # Compare to S&P 500 if available
    if sp500_1year is not None and len(sp500_1year) > 0:
        sp500_return_1y = ((sp500_1year['Close'].iloc[-1] / sp500_1year['Close'].iloc[0]) - 1) * 100
        outperformance_1y = return_1y - sp500_return_1y
        print(f" S&P 500 1Y Return: {sp500_return_1y:+.1f}%")
        print(f" Outperformance: {outperformance_1y:+.1f}%")
    
    # Monthly performance breakdown
    print(f"\n MONTHLY PERFORMANCE (Last 12 Months):")
    monthly_returns = []
    for i in range(12):
        month_end = end_date_1y - timedelta(days=30*i)
        month_start = month_end - timedelta(days=30)
        
        month_data = stock_1year[(stock_1year.index >= month_start) & (stock_1year.index <= month_end)]
        if len(month_data) > 1:
            month_return = ((month_data['Close'].iloc[-1] / month_data['Close'].iloc[0]) - 1) * 100
            monthly_returns.append((month_end.strftime('%Y-%m'), month_return))
    
    # Show last 6 months
    for month, ret in monthly_returns[:6]:
        print(f" {month}: {ret:+.1f}%")

print(f"\n" + "="*60)

    ax1.bar(puts_data['strike'], -puts_data['volume'], alpha=0.7, color='red',

    ax1.axvline(current_price, color='blue', linestyle='--', linewidth=2,

    ax1.set_xlabel('Strike Price ($)')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Volume (Calls +, Puts -)')
    ax1.legend()
    ax1.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    # 2. Implied Volatility Smile
    # Combine calls and puts for IV analysis
    all_strikes = pd.concat([
        calls_data[['strike', 'impliedVolatility']].assign(type='Call'),
        puts_data[['strike', 'impliedVolatility']].assign(type='Put')
    ])
    
    # Filter for reasonable strikes (within 20% of current price)
    price_range = current_price * 0.2
    iv_data = all_strikes[
        (all_strikes['strike'] >= current_price - price_range) & 
        (all_strikes['strike'] <= current_price + price_range)
    ].copy()
    
    if not iv_data.empty:
        calls_iv = iv_data[iv_data['type'] == 'Call']
        puts_iv = iv_data[iv_data['type'] == 'Put']
        
        ax2.scatter(calls_iv['strike'], calls_iv['impliedVolatility'], 
                   color='green', alpha=0.7, label='Calls IV', s=50)
        ax2.scatter(puts_iv['strike'], puts_iv['impliedVolatility'], 
                   color='red', alpha=0.7, label='Puts IV', s=50)
        
        ax2.axvline(current_price, color='blue', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
        ax2.set_title(clean_text_for_display('Implied Volatility Smile'))
        ax2.set_xlabel('Strike Price ($)')
        ax2.set_ylabel('Implied Volatility')
        ax2.legend()
        ax2.grid(True, alpha=0.3)

# Additional Technical Analysis - RSI and Bollinger Bands
def calculate_rsi(prices, window=14):
    """Calculate Relative Strength Index"""
    delta = prices.diff()
    gain = (delta.where(delta > 0, 0)).rolling(window=window).mean()
    loss = (-delta.where(delta < 0, 0)).rolling(window=window).mean()
    rs = gain / loss
    rsi = 100 - (100 / (1 + rs))
    return rsi

def calculate_bollinger_bands(prices, window=20, num_std=2):
    """Calculate Bollinger Bands"""
    rolling_mean = prices.rolling(window=window).mean()
    rolling_std = prices.rolling(window=window).std()
    upper_band = rolling_mean + (rolling_std * num_std)
    lower_band = rolling_mean - (rolling_std * num_std)
    return upper_band, rolling_mean, lower_band
